# Standard Project Rules

## Core Principles
- Favor clarity over cleverness.
- Keep changes minimal and focused on the requested outcome.
- Preserve existing behavior unless the task explicitly requires a change.
- Optimize for readability, maintainability, and predictable outcomes.

## Code Quality
- Follow the existing project structure and naming patterns.
- Write small, single-purpose functions and avoid deep nesting.
- Prefer explicit error handling over silent failures.
- Remove dead code and avoid introducing unused variables or imports.
- Use `TypeScript` for new code in this project.
- In TypeScript, do not use `any`, `as` casts, or type assertions; use precise types and type guards.

## Testing And Validation
- Validate functional changes with the most relevant local checks.
- Always run a TypeScript/type/error check (`tsc` or project equivalent) for substantive code changes.
- Fix newly introduced type and runtime errors when feasible before considering work complete.
- Add or update tests when behavior changes.
- Do not skip failing checks; fix root causes when feasible.
- Call out any unverified paths when full validation is not possible.

## Documentation
- Update docs or inline comments when behavior, interfaces, or setup changes.
- Keep comments concise and explanatory; avoid obvious commentary.
- Record assumptions and tradeoffs when they affect implementation choices.

## Git And Collaboration
- Keep commits scoped to a single concern.
- Use clear commit messages that explain intent and impact.
- Never commit secrets, credentials, or environment-specific sensitive data.
- Do not rewrite shared history unless explicitly requested.

## Security And Reliability
- Validate external inputs at trust boundaries.
- Use least-privilege defaults for configuration and permissions.
- Avoid logging sensitive data.
- Prefer safe defaults and explicit opt-ins for risky behavior.

## Performance
- Avoid premature optimization; focus first on correctness.
- Measure before optimizing hotspots.
- Keep network and I/O operations intentional and bounded.

## Accessibility And UX (When Applicable)
- Ensure keyboard accessibility and visible focus states.
- Preserve semantic markup and readable contrast.
- Provide clear loading, empty, and error states.
- For typography in UI code, use Tailwind text size utilities (for example `text-xs`, `text-sm`, `text-base`, `text-lg`, `text-xl`) instead of arbitrary font-size values.
